<div class='bookAuthorProfile__about'>

<span id="freeTextContainer573292972621021155"><a href='https://megwaiteclayton.com' rel='nofollow noopener'>Meg Waite Clayton</a> is a <em>New York Times</em> bestselling author of 8 novels, including THE POSTMISTRESS OF PARIS (Harper, Nov 30, 2021), an IndieNext pick, Publisher&apos;s Weekly notable book for fall, and Canadian LoanStars #2 pick the San Francisco Chronicle calls “Gripping … an evocative love story layered with heroism and intrigue — the film ‘Casablanca’ if Rick had an artsy bent … powerful.” <br/><br/>Her prior b</span>
  <span id="freeText573292972621021155" style="display:none"><a href="https://megwaiteclayton.com" rel="nofollow noopener">Meg Waite Clayton</a> is a <em>New York Times</em> bestselling author of 8 novels, including THE POSTMISTRESS OF PARIS (Harper, Nov 30, 2021), an IndieNext pick, Publisher's Weekly notable book for fall, and Canadian LoanStars #2 pick the San Francisco Chronicle calls “Gripping … an evocative love story layered with heroism and intrigue — the film ‘Casablanca’ if Rick had an artsy bent … powerful.” <br /><br />Her prior books include the international bestseller and National Jewish Book Award finalist THE LAST TRAIN TO LONDON, the #1 Amazon fiction bestseller BEAUTIFUL EXILES, the Langum-Prize honored national bestseller <a href="http://megwaiteclayton.com" rel="nofollow noopener">THE RACE FOR PARIS</a> -- recommended reading by Glamour Magazine and the BBC, and an Indie Next Booksellers' pick -- and <a href="http://megwaiteclayton.com/book_WednesdaySisters.shtml" rel="nofollow noopener">THE WEDNESDAY SISTERS</a>, one of Entertainment Weekly's "25 Essential Best Friend Novels" of all time. Her THE LANGUAGE OF LIGHT was a finalist for the Bellwether Prize (now PEN/Bellwether Prize), and she's written essays for The New York Times, The Los Angeles Times, Runner's World, Writer's Digest and lots of other swanky publications she never imagined she might!</span>
  <a data-text-id="573292972621021155" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

